**Problem 5(b)** Show  for all 2D polynomials
$$
p(x,y) = \sum_{k=0}^n \sum_{j=0}^m c_{kj} x^k y^j
$$
that
$$
\begin{align*}
p(x + a œµ_x, y + b œµ_y) &= p(x,y) + a  {‚àÇ p \over ‚àÇ x} œµ_x  +  b  {‚àÇ p \over ‚àÇ y}   œµ_y.
\end{align*}
$$

**SOLUTION**
By linearity it suffices to consider monomials $x^k y^j$. Assume it is true
for all lower degree polynomials with the degree $0$ case holding trivially.
If $j = 0$ we  have:
$$
(x + a œµ_x)^k = (x + a œµ_x)(x + a œµ_x)^{k-1} = 
 (x + a œµ_x)(x^{k-1} + a (k-1) x^{k-2} œµ_x) = 
  x^k  + a k x^{k-1} œµ_x
$$
 and similarly for $k = 0$. For $k,j \neq 0$ we can use the previous cases to get:
$$
(x + a œµ_x)^k (y + b œµ_y)^j = (x^k + k a x^{k-1} œµ_x) (y^j + j b y^{j-1} œµ_y)= 
x^k y^j + k a x^{k-1} y^j œµ_x + b j x^k y^{j-1}
$$
**END**

